<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n41109c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41109c">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41109c"> 109(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> pepper, red, white / &amp; black</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Scott (p. 36) has &ldquo;mahazzim (for mah&aacute;zim), al Zerdukkaut (for al- Zardakh&aacute;n)&rdquo; and &ldquo;munnaskif (for man&aacute;skif) al fillfillee.&rdquo; Of the former he notes (p. 414) &ldquo;What this composition is I cannot define: it may be translated compound of saffron, yoke <font color="green">[sic]</font> of egg or of yellowish drugs.&rdquo; He evidently confounds it with the Pers. Zard-i-Kh&aacute;yah = yoke <font color="green">[sic]</font> of egg. Of the second he says &ldquo;compound of <mark>peppers, red, white and black</mark>.&rdquo; <small> Richard F. Burton, trans. <a name="RBTE3" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE3"><cite title="source">Supplemental Nights to the Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) V, 55n3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
